definition: "Lipoprotein(a), or Lp(a), is a lipoprotein particle similar in structure to LDL but with an additional protein called apolipoprotein(a) &#8212; abbreviated apo(a) &#8212; covalently attached to the ApoB-100 protein. The apo(a) protein has structural similarities to plasminogen (a clot-dissolving protein), which gives Lp(a) its unique pathological properties: it is both atherogenic (promotes plaque formation like LDL) and thrombogenic (inhibits clot dissolution, promoting clot formation on ruptured plaques). Lp(a) levels are almost entirely determined by genetics &#8212; specifically by the LPA gene on chromosome 6 &#8212; and are largely unaffected by diet, exercise, or most medications."
